Both Iraq and Afghanistan are huge countries not much smaller than the size of Germany, and their respective costs would dwarf even the most ambitious plans in Western Europe. It would also be hard to pull off an embargo on minimum wage.

> Eliminating the minimum wage would remove entire segments of the population from the employment pool.

That's racist and classist bullshit.

> Investments in middle income and productive assets, e.g. regular beats. Or a useful, preventatively-oriented program, such as pulse oximetry, for homeless people and marginalized communities affected by the opioid crisis.

At its core, drug prohibition is a massive racist/wealthist campaign to further entrench socially exploitative wealth disparities. And no, interventions to deal with that are not a substitute for eliminating the prohibition. Prohibition does what it says on the tin: it does not merely provide an income, it also provides a **primitive** source of income. The system isn't a lifeboat where you can just screw all the social problems of the world. For obvious reasons, you can't pull a minimum wage hike while simultaneously ***abandoning the entire fucking population to rampant social and health issues***. Maybe that's a reason to look at alternatives to keeping the horseshoe up. Like, for example, occasionally looking at why such amounts of people are hiring protection rackets and gangs in the first place.
